🔥 25. What is Logging?
✅ Answer (Interview Ready)

Logging is used to record application events, errors, and flow during execution so that we can monitor, debug, and trace issues in real-time or production.

🧠 Real-Time Explanation

In day-to-day projects:

We don’t use System.out.println()
Instead, we use logging frameworks like:
SLF4J → Logging API (interface)
Logback → Logging implementation (actual engine)

🔄 How They Work Together
Application Code → SLF4J → Logback → Console / File / Server
SLF4J = abstraction (what you call)
Logback = implementation (what actually logs)

💻 Example (Real Project Style)
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;
class OrderService {
    private static final Logger log = LoggerFactory.getLogger(OrderService.class);
    public void placeOrder() {
        log.info("Order started");
        try {
            // business logic
            log.debug("Processing payment");
        } catch (Exception e) {
            log.error("Error occurred while placing order", e);
        }
        log.info("Order completed");
    }
}
